<p>almost half of uk drivers let their car insurance renew automatically. each year, that collective inertia costs the country £560 million in unnecessary premiums. the average overpayment per driver: £82.</p>

<p>that's the car insurance auto-renewal tax, and 47% of drivers pay it without ever seeing the breakdown.</p>

<h4>why auto-renewal costs more</h4>

<p>when your policy auto-renews, you're not getting the same deal as last year — you're getting last year's deal, adjusted upward. the insurer factors in inflation, claims trends, and their own pricing targets. then they send you a renewal document that looks almost identical to last year's, so it's easy to skim, approve, and forget.</p>

<p>the fca now requires insurers to show your previous year's premium alongside the new quote. but close to half of drivers surveyed said they didn't notice this information. the problem isn't visibility — it's attention.</p>

<h4>the cost in context</h4>

<p>at £635 for a comprehensive policy, uk car insurance is near historic highs. an extra £82 on top of that might not feel like a crisis, but it compounds. over five years of auto-renewing without checking, that's £410 in unnecessary payments. enough to cover a year of home contents insurance, or a decent dinner every month for four months.</p>

<h4>what perch. does differently</h4>

<p>a calendar reminder to "check car insurance" is vague. it doesn't tell you what changed, whether the new price is fair, or whether you have leverage to negotiate. perch. extracts the actual numbers from your renewal document, compares them to last year, and gives you a clear verdict: renew, cancel, or renegotiate.</p>

